g.text: Each identified symbol (representing variables, functions, classes, interfaces, etc.) is
created and added to the symbol table. The symbols capture the scope and type information.
The compiler identifies the various scopes defined
by blocks, functions, and modules within the AST.
Using the symbol table and the scopes, ensure that all
types are used consistently and according to their definitions.
The compiler transforms the TypeScript AST into a JavaScript AST by removing type annotations
and converting TypeScript-specific language constructs into their JavaScript equivalents.
If the target ECMAScript version is older than the one used in the source,
TypeScript code is "downleveled" to a compatible JavaScript version.
The transformed JavaScript AST is then converted into executable JavaScript code.
Alongside the JavaScript code, source maps can be generated to map
the transpiled code back to the original TypeScript, aiding in debugging.
The compiler generates type declaration files that describe
the types used in the TypeScript source.
